<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>“Working for quality</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he Voice of the Listener &amp; Viewer (VLV) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">[FBB0030]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.  Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV believes that public service broadcasting is the jewel in the crown of the media landscape of the UK, helping to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure excellence and diversity in programming and to underpin the quality of the national debate. A publicly owned BBC is the cornerstone of this topology and needs to be of sufficient  scale and scope, to meet citizens’ expectations and deliver its Royal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Charter remit.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s purpose should be to serve the communications needs, rights and interests of UK citizens. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All the BBC’s channels and services need to demonstrate clear public service value.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The VLV believes that public funding is necessary if</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the BBC is to continue to meet the expectations placed upon it. The licence fee, while not ideal, remains the fairest and most effective way of funding the BBC’s core activities for the foreseeable future and needs to be set at a realistic level that allo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ws the BBC to plan with confidence</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Funding  from the licence fee should be protected for use by core BBC services and not diverted to other purposes; and the BBC needs to be able to demonstrate that it is using its money effectively and efficiently to dis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">charge its Charter commitments.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.   Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Voice of the Listener &amp; Viewer (VLV) is an independent, non-profit-making membership association, free from political, commercial and sectarian affiliations, working for quality and diversity in Brit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ish broadcasting. VLV represents the interests of listeners and viewers as citizens and consumers across the full range of broadcasting issues. VLV is concerned with the structures, regulation, funding and institutions that underpin the British Broadcastin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g system.  VLV is a charitable company limited by guarantee. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For 30 years VLV has played a unique role in keeping a citizen’s eye on major legislative proposals and action taken by regulators and broadcasters, enabling the voice of consumers to be heard, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">independently from the interests of political parties, industry players and other pressure groups.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.  What should the BBC be for and what</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Public service broadcasting refers to TV programmes that are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> broadcast for the public benefit rather than for purely commercial purposes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> (Ofcom)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><a name="a2"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ofcom measures delivery of programming by public service broadcasters</span></a><a name="n7"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> against four objectives, or "public service purposes": </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(a) informing our understanding of the world</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(b) stimulating knowledge and learning</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(c) reflecting UK cultural identity; and </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(d) representing diversity and alternative viewpoints.</span><a name="n8"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV supports these criteria of measurement and believes they are still fit for purpose. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.  What is the BBC for?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Lord Reith, the BBC's first Director-General, said that the responsibility of public service broadcasting was to "carry into the greatest number of homes everything that was best in every department of human knowledge, endeavour and achievement; and to avo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">id whatever was or might be hurtful."</span><a name="n3"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s mission to inform, educate and entertain still seems appropriate to VLV. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These are high ambitions, but VLV applauds them and believes the BBC needs to continue to take an ambitious, original, distinctive ap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proach to public service content which appeals to a wide audience. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">its Building Public Value</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> policy document in the run up to Charter Renewal in 2004, the BBC emphasised the public value of the BBC, based on three pillars – universal access, fairness an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d equity and accountability. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">While commercial broadcasters aim to return value to their shareholders or owners, the BBC exists to create public value. In other words, it aims to serve its audiences not just as consumers, but as members of a wider society,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> with programmes and services which, while seeking to inform, </span><a name="_"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">educate and entertain audiences, also serve wider public purposes. Public value is a measure of the BBC’s contribution to the quality of life in the UK. </span></a><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV believes that these public value am</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bitions and its vision </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to be the most creative organisation in the world</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should remain at the heart of what the BBC does and that the BBC should continue to aim to broadcast a high quality, inclusive service which is free at the poi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t of access and is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">valued by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> populations around the world. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As stated in the Agreement which accompanies the BBC Charter: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The content of the BBC’s UK Public Services must be high quality, challenging, original, innovative and engaging, with every programme or item of content</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> exhibiting at least one of those characteristics.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">High quality, imaginative and cost-effective programmes - and other services - are currently provided by the BBC on the principle of universal availability and on a ‘free to air’ basis throughout the Unite</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Kingdom; and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the programmes are not only for the adults who pay the licence fees but for the children who</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> do not and who benefit from both educational content and general programming.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  As an example of what economists have referred to as ‘merit goods’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hese services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contribute to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">our understanding of the world and our general levels of knowledge and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">well-being</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as well as meeting the needs of individuals. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In summary, the BBC makes a significant contribution to our general quality of life. But it also co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ntributes to life-long learning, to economic development and to the ‘creative industries’ in Britain. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.  How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">By its own admission, the BBC has fallen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">short of its own aspirations during this period in terms of public trust and value for money, with specific reference to executive pay. However it appears from research that the public still value the BBC and appreciate its services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, while expecting high s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tandards of accountability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Despite </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its difficulties </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">during this period</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the BBC continues to fulfil its public purposes as set out in the 2006 Charter. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Turning to specific issues, and particularly to the purpose to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Stimulate Creativity and Cultural Exc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ellence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the apparent decline in serious drama and classical music has concerned VLV members. The total cut to the BBC Four drama budget is particularly regretted. We are pleased to acknowledge that BBC Two still contains cultural and arts-based programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and programmes for specialist or minority interests that would not find a place on a free-to-air commercial channel. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">With reference</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Representing the UK, its nations, regions and communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, evidence shows significant opposition to cuts in local radi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o. Our members believe that BBC Local Radio assists the process of local democracy by holding local politicians to account for their decisions and actions. They fear this function may be diminished because of cuts to local radio budgets. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV assumes that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in due course the BBC Trust will publish an audit of the achievements of the BBC since the 2006 Charter was established so that licence fee payers will be able to assess the BBC's performance in delivering its public purposes. Until such a time as this re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">search is published, VLV would not like to make any further comment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6.  Are the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is VLV’s view that the public purposes are the right ones. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.  What scope, scale and remit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">should the BBC have? </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC exists as a conscious democratic, social and cultural intervention in the market in order to achieve the public purposes laid out in the Charter. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the multi-channel, internet-enabled world many households in Britain have access to a wide range of sources of information and entertainment. However, the take-up of new channels and services has also meant considerably increased monthly costs for consu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mers. In this situation the provision of a basic package of high quality services for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> homes becomes a high priority for reasons of social equity, cultural cohesion, educational development and employability. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC is only able to fulfil its public v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">alue ambitions because of its scale and reach. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Having followed and contributed to policy debates for decades, VLV has been, and remains, concerned that the commercial sector is allowed to set the tone of this debate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> without producing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">convincing evidence o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the BBC’s detrimental effects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on the emergence of successful new services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The communications world is one of a multiplicity of content and service providers today. Commercial publishers, rivals and opponents of the BBC criticise the scale and scope of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the BBC’s intervention in the market. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">They say there is no possibility of the market ‘failing’; indeed, that by distorting the market, the BBC is itself creating failure (in that, for example, commercial publishers won’t launch new products in many content areas because they fear the BBC has o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r will colonise the space). Against this, VLV would put forward a full ‘market failure’ argument. ‘Market failure’ does not simply refer to whether or not there are other providers in the marketplace. It refers to the fact that, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">whatever the number of prov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">iders in the market at any given time, the market may still fail the citizen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">if there isn’t a wide range of high quality, diverse and informative programming, especially in genres which may not be considered commercially attractive. We note the importance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the BBC’s role in developing the UK market and skills to the benefit of all players; and that there is evidence from a number of European markets that the most successful are those where there is a strong public sector presence alongside the commercial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">players.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, while VLV believes the BBC needs to be of a size and scale to ensure adequate reach and impact, we would warn against the tendency of the BBC to want to do everything, and encourage the BBC Trust to ensure that every penny of the licence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fee is spent in a way which results in public value. VLV believes the BBC Trust’s Public Value Tests are a sufficient tool to ensure that any new services the BBC proposes are examined in a market context and prevent the BBC from creating new services whic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h do not demonstrate sufficient public value.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8.  Should the BBC’s output and services be provided to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences? </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV believes that the BBC needs to engage as wide an audience as possible across all its services. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This ambition is explicitly stated in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Building Public Value</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> BBC policy document in 2004:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘politicians and the public decided very early on that broadc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">asting should be placed in the public sphere of our national life. They believed that everyone has a right to high quality broadcast services, regardless of income, age, sex, race, religion or where they live. This is why the BBC was founded according to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">hree public principles: </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Universality– it is for everyone and should be freely available to everyone; </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.02pt; padding-left:4.98pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Fairness and equity– because it is held in common it should fairly reflect the needs and interests of all its different users; </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.2pt; padding-left:3.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Accountability– collectiv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e ownership confers on the British public the right of collective accountability and the power to monitor the performance and guide the future of the BBC through their civic institutions</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV believes that the BBC needs to provide services which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are charact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">erised by equity and excellence and delivered to a wide range of audiences. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s value should not be measured simply in terms of audience viewing figures, but rather in terms of the quality of and need for the services it provides. It is essential that the BBC’s value is measured by the experience of the individual and the go</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">od to society as a whole. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9.  What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC should continue to produce programmes across all genres. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV believes the current arran</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gements with quotas for independent production and the W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">indow of Creative Competition (WOCC)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are working well to ensure a thriving UK production sector as well as maintaining production and skills within the BBC. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">10.  How have the BBC’s commercial activit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ies during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV believes the BBC’s commercial activities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">during the current Charter fit with the public purposes and have achieved an adequate return. From its 2012/13 figures it is clear BBC Worldwide is providing the BBC with extra revenue and it appears to be growing with headline profit up 1% in 2012/13. Sin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ce 2007 BBC Worldwide has provided total returns to the BBC of over £1bn.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that BBC Worldwide’s activities should continue beyond 2016 following the same purposes and methods. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">11.  What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ays of distributing content?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The ‘sixth public purpose’ of the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In promoting its other purposes, helping to deliver to the public the benefit of emerging communications technologies and services and, in addition, taking a leading role in the switchover</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to digital television</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV supports BBC research into future technology and the distribution of content only where that research promotes its other purposes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Thus it is VLV’s view that the BBC should not be required to contribute any funding to the roll </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">out of broadband infrastructure, for example. To the extent that this cannot be funded by the commercial infrastructure providers, it should be funded by general taxation, because it is part of the nation’s social and cultural policy rather than the respon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sibility of a single broadcaster. Not only will other broadcasters and service providers, including those with very limited or no public service obligations, benefit from this work, it also means diverting licence fee income, contributed by citizens to run</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the BBC.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">12.  How should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the BBC be funded beyond 2016? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that the licence fee, while not ideal, remains the fairest and most effective way of funding the BBC for the foreseeable future and that it should rise in line with RPI. We believe that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the licence fee has played an important part in underpinning the BBC’s independence from political interference.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Public support for the licence fee as the best option for funding the BBC is higher than it is for any other form of funding. </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This is not surprising, as the licence fee, in real terms, is at a lower level than 20 years ago, despite the huge increase in services now by the BBC.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="border-color:#000000; border-style:solid; border-width:0.5pt; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">13.  Is there a case for distributing funding for public service content more widely beyond the BBC?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">V</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LV does not believe there should be a separate distribution of funds for public service content beyond the funding provided to the BBC. The BBC and other public service broadcasters should continue to commission public service content from independent prod</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ucers - a form of distribution of funding for public service content in itself.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV does not support the licence fee settlement reached in December 2011 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the current Government because it effectively diverted money from BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programme-making bu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dgets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> We viewed this move as a method of reducing Government spending on obligations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which were not agreed as obligations of the BBC in the last Charter. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This type of ‘top-slicing’ undermines the clarity of the direct relationship between the licence fee payer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the BBC. We believe that it is very important for the BBC to do more to establish a sense of ownership among its licence payers. This will be extremely difficult if the Government diverts funds for other purposes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">14</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">  What comparisons can be made with the provision of public service content in other countries? </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A recent survey conducted by the European Audiovisual Observatory showed that in 2011 the BBC’s TV audience market share, as a proportion of the public funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in its revenues, was the highest of any European public broadcaster except Denmark. It is probably the most respected, the most envied and the most commercially successful broadcaster in Europe.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Unlike some public broadcasters in other European countries,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the BBC has never been located within a government department or grant-aided by a minister with money drawn from general taxation. And it has been accepted, by both government and the BBC, that it should be independent, operating at a distance from the go</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vernment of the day. Although in the 90 years of the BBC’s history there have been examples of government interference, or attempted interference, essentially the BBC remains independent of political control.  This is one of its key characteristics.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">15.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Clearly, the last 18 months have seen significant problems relating to the governance of the BBC. It is difficult to judge at this stage whether these stem from a fundamental prob</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lem with the present structure or from practical failings in the way in which the structure has been operated. We therefore welcome the review commissioned by the Director-General and Chairman, aimed at identifying and remedying the key issues. We would re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">serve further comments until we have seen the outcome of that review.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">More broadly, we welcomed recent comments by the Secretary of State when she said the BBC needs to focus on immediate issues which need to be resolved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The immediate priority is that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he BBC gets its house in order. Obviously the Charter Review is in 2016 and all of these other issues I’m sure will be part of that. But we should not distract away from the most important thing at the moment and we should not let other things get in the w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ay”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">16.  In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional frame work for the BBC?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VLV supports the constitutional framework of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Building Public Value, page 8</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> http://www.bbc.co.uk/aboutthebbc/insidethebbc/whoweare/mission_and_values/</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt">Research by </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt"> YouGov shows similar </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt">results when people are asked </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt">their preferred means of funding the BBC </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt">- </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt">48% backing the licence fee; 27% for advertising; 13% for subscription-only; and 6% a combination of advertising and subscription. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt; font-style:italic">YouGov for Prospect, 1,712 GB </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt; font-style:italic">ad</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt; font-style:italic">ults 18+, February 2013 (online</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt; font-style:italic">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>